      "content": "Proponents of the genetic explanation often point to the fact that environmental factors, such as nutrition and education, can only account for a small portion of the variation in IQ scores within a given population. They argue that if environmental factors were the primary driver of IQ differences, we would expect to see smaller or even diminishing gaps between racial groups as they become more similar in terms of education and socioeconomic status. However, they claim that the gaps persist, suggesting that there must be an underlying genetic component that is not being fully captured by environmental explanations. They also often cite the fact that IQ scores are highly heritable, with estimates suggesting that 40-80% of the variation in IQ can be attributed to genetics, which they argue supports the idea that genetics play a significant role in shaping cognitive abilities.",
